Ways to Shorten Your Runway
text:
Being a founder is hard.

And it’s even harder when you don’t master a topic you need to deal with. It’s easy to get impressed by a candidate, or an advisor, who name-drops concepts that look shiny to achieve their goal: sell themselves.

It happens with technical candidates who oversell themselves to business founders, and the other way around: technical founders can be fooled by a varnish of knowledge or new concepts.

I had a lot of fun describingthe most common traps technical founders should not fall into, when they need to deal with a business topic, for the 1st time.

In other words, if a candidate or vendor sells one of these topics to you as the solution to a burning issue, in 95% of cases it’s a red flag.

Full post here: https://www.getlago.com/blog/3-traps-for-unwary-technical-founders

Ask HN: Do you own or run a forum in a niche market?
text:
I'm working to build a forum for a niche segment. User acquisition is not a problem, I already have social groups with 15K active users/day. I thought it would be good to HN ideas and feedback in the process so I can avoid pit holes and plan the path right.

1. What framework did you chose? 2. How to tackle Content moderation and maintenance? 3. How to monetize? Ads or Sponsor referrals or other ways?

Any other things to consider, I'm not foreseeing?

Ask HN: Beside sports what other job offer a fine mix of tension and resolution?
text:
Off the top of my head I can only come up with quasi-sport type of jobs such as professional poker player, professional bridge player etc.

In essence a professional player living in Vegas or Atlantic City. That or also being a pro at whatever card game is most popular in Macau.

Does anybody else have some ideas?

Ideally the mix of tension and resolution is about the same as pro-sports. Meaning 6-10 days of tension build up and then a competitive event marking resolution, with the cycle repeating itself.
